.TH ROGOMATIC 6 "2026 Mar 19"
.UC 4
.SH NAME
rogomatic, rgmgene, rgmhist, rgmscatter \- Automatically Exploring The Dungeons of Doom
.SH SYNOPSIS
.I rogomatic
[
.B \-h
]
[
.B \-V
]
[
.B \-c
]
[
.B \-d
]
[
.BI \-D\  rgmdir
]
[
.B \-e
]
[
.B \-f
.I rogue
]
[
.B \-H
]
[
.BI \-p\  roguelog
]
[
.B \-r
]
[
.B \-s
]
[
.BI \-S\  ROGOSEED
]
[
.B \-t
]
[
.B \-u
]
[
.B \-w
]
[
.B \-E
]
[
.I file
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.I Rog-O-Matic
(hereafter referred to as
.BR rogomatic )
is a computer fantasy game with a newer twist.
It is CRT (Cathode Rat Tube) oriented and the
object of the game is to automatically survive the attacks of various
monsters and get a lot of gold, rather than having to actually type the
required commands yourself.
.PP
The
.B rogomatic
plays the game of
.B rogue
on your behalf while you watch.
.PP
Once you have entered the world of
.B rogomatic
you will stay there, passively watching the game unfold before you much
like a catatonic teenager watching television.
Should you wish to intervene, type the
.B t
command and
.B rogomatic
will enter transparent mode.
.PP
When
.B rogomatic
launches
.B rogue
via the
.B player
program, it sets the
.B $ROGUEOPTS
environment to a value such that the
rogue player name used will start with
.BR rogo\- ,
and set the rogue score path to
.BR @RMGDIR@/rogue.scr ,
which is
.B NOT
the default rogue score file.
Thus by default,
.B rogomatic
game stats will not compete with the humans.
.B COMMANDS
section below for details on commands, and on transparent mode.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h
Print the usage message,
and exit with a status of
.BR 2 .
.TP
.B \-V
Print the
.B rogomatic
version string
and exit with a status of
.BR 2 .
.TP
.B \-c
Turns on cheat mode
and use use trap arrows.
See also the
.B c
command in the in transparent mode in the
.B COMMANDS
section below.
.TP
.B \-d
Use a UTC date and time sub-directory under rogomatic directory path
to store files.
.sp
By default,
.B rogomatic
creates and uses files under:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.IR @RGMDIR@
.in -0.5i
.sp
The
.B \-d
command line option will creates and uses files under:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@ /YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS
is the year, month, day, hour, minute and second, in the UTC timezone,
of when player command started.
.TP
.BI \-D \ rgmdir
Change the rogomatic directory path to
.IR rgmdir .
.sp
The use of
.B \-d
command line option combined with
.BI \-D \ rgmdir
will case
.B rogomatic
to create and use files under:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.IR rgmdir /YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS
.in -0.5i
.TP
.B \-e
Turns on logging.
See also the
.B e
command in transparent mode.
.TP
.BI \-f \ rogue
Set the path of
.BR rogue .
.sp
By default,
.B rogomatic
first looks for
.B ./rogue
in the current directory before looking for
.B rogue
in the default installation location of:
.BR @BINDIR@/rogue .
.sp
The
.B rogomatic
command might be able to  play with versions 3.6, 5.2, 5.3, 5.4, 5.4.4, and 5.4.5.
.sp
You can run
.B rogomatic
on modified rogues using this option,
but be warned that the interface must be completely compatible with
one of the standard versions of
.B rogue
listed, and the version number
printed must be either "3.6," "5.2," "5.3", "5.4", or "5.4.5".
.sp
.BR IMPORTANT\ NOTE :
Only
.B rogue version 5.4.5
as found in the GitHub repo:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.I https://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4
.in -0.5i
.sp
has been tested with this version of
.B rogomatic
While other versions of rogue may work, only
.B rogue version 5.4.5
is now supported.
.TP
.B \-H
Disable the so-called rogomatic "\fIhalftime show\fP".
.sp
When
.B rogomatic
detects that
.B rogue
has reached level 2, it plays a short character based "movie" on the screen.
.sp
The use of
.B \-t
or
.B \-E
implies
.BR \-H .
.sp
Historically, this option was
.BR \-h ,
however recently that option became the "help option",
and so it was named as
.BR \-H .
.TP
.BI \-p \ roguelog
Replay the
.I roguelog
rogue log file.
.sp
The default rogue log file is:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@ /roguelog
.in -0.5i
.TP
.B \-r
Restore a saved rogue game.
.sp
Without a final
.I file
command line option, run
.B rogue
with the
.BR \-r \ @RGMDIR@/rogue.sav
command line option and restore
the rogue game stored in that file.
.sp
If a final
.I file
command line option is given, run
.B rogue
with the
.BI \-r \ file
command line option to
the rogue game stored
.IR file .
.TP
.B \-s
Print the
.B rogomatic
scoreboard.
.sp
The default rogomatic scoreboard is:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@/rgmscore version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
.sp
If a final
.I file
command line option is given, then the rogomatic scoreboard printed will be from:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI file version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
.TP
.B \-t
Terse mode.
In terse mode,
.B rogomatic
will only print a summary after each level explored.
.TP
.B \-u
Start up in user mode.
This tells
.B rogomatic
to start up in transparent mode, so the user can type commands before
.B rogomatic
starts exploring level 1.
.TP
.B \-w
Start up in watched mode.
.TP
.B \-E
Start up in emacs mode.
.SH COMMANDS
.PP
The
.B t
command
will cause
.B rogomatic
will enter transparent mode.
.PP
In transparent mode, you can type several commands, the
most useful of which is the
.B ?
command, which prints out the next help line.
Press the
.B ?
key repeatedly to see all of the help.
Some useful commands are:
.B h
.B j
.B k
.B l
.B H
.B J
.B K
.B L
.B b
.B n
.B y
.B u
.B f
.B s
.B >
.B <
.B S
.B Q.
These have the same meaning as in normal
.BR rogue .
To return to
.B rogomatic
mode, type the
.B t
command again.
.PP
Some useful commands are:
.TP
.B t
.I Toggle,
toggles the setting of the
.I transparent
mode flag.
In transparent mode,
.B rogomatic
will not automatically attack monsters, pick up treasure, or explore
around.
Unfortunately, there is no way to enter complicated commands
like
.I quaff
or
.I read
in transparent mode.
Typing any
.B rogue
command, or single-step command also enables transparent mode.
.TP
.B Q
.I Quit,
tells
.B rogomatic
to quit the game.
The score is logged in the score file, and possibly the
.B rogue
top ten, and the game is terminated.
.TP
.B S
.I Save,
the game is saved to the default save file, set by the
.I <file>
argument to
.I rogomatic
or the
.I ROGUEOPTS
environment variable.
The game may be restarted later.
.TP
.B c
.I Cheat,
tells
.B rogomatic
to take advantage of idiosyncracies in the
.B rogue
game to get a higher score.
This is unfortunately necessary to allow fair
competition with other human top ten players who take advantage of the same
bugs.
.sp
Note that this option should only be used on very old 3.6 version
.BR rogue ,
since the VMS version does not exhibit the same bugs.
When playing against
.B rogue
version 5.2 and later, no cheating is done, since the bugs are not widely known and used by
human competition.
.TP
.B d
.I Debugging,
toggles the debugging flag, which is useless to non-wizard
players (although it is entertaining if your terminal has reverse video).
.TP
.B e
.I Echoing,
causes a copy of the game to be written to file
.I roguelog
in the current directory.
Typing
.B e
a second time closes the log file.
When the game is ended, the roguelog
file is renamed to <killer>.<level>.<score> so if a troll killed poor
.B rogomatic
on level 14 leaving him with a score of 3088, the file would be named
.I trol.14.3088.
Note that only the first four characters of the killer are used.
The
.B -p
option will replay a saved game.
Additionally, a stop action command
(carriage return gives a single step) has been added.
.TP
.B i
.I Inventory,
dumps the current inventory on the screen.
.TP
.B m
.I Monster list,
shows the current long term memory evaluation of the monsters.
.B rogomatic
nows keeps a long term memory file (for each version of
.BR rogue )
in the
score directory, and records the meanness of each monster it finds.
This command prints out the letter, name, and strength of each monster.
Strength is listed as three numbers: expected damage (scaled by 10) and
maximum damage (unscaled) are shown in parentheses, and the mean number
of arrows required to kill a monster is shown in square brackets.
.TP
.B CR
.I Single step,
a carriage return enables
.I transparent
mode, and causes
.B rogomatic
to single-step.
The command sent is printed at the
bottom right hand of the screen.
.TP
.B /
.I Snapshot,
a timestamp, the current screen, and the current inventory are appended
to file
.I snapshot.rgm
in the current directory.
.TP
.B $
.I Weaponrank,
dumps
.BR rogomatic 's
current estimate of his weapons rankings.
.TP
.B %
.I Armorrank,
dumps
.BR rogomatic 's
current estimate of his armor rankings.
.TP
.B =
.I Ringrank,
dumps
.BR rogomatic 's
current estimate of his ring rankings.
.TP
.B -
.I Status,
prints out a status line indicating various things like whether
.BR rogomatic 's
is confused, has red hands, is wearing cursed armor or wielding a cursed
weapon, and which monsters have been genocided.
It also prints the number of turns elapsed in the game.
.TP
.B `
.I Summary,
a backquote prints a short summary of the game.
.TP
.B ~
.I Version,
prints the version of
.B rogue
and
.B rogomatic
being used.
It also prints the current goal score.
.TP
.B G
.I Genotype,
displays the settings of the genetically learned parameters of the
genotype playing now.
See section
.I Genes
for more information about these parameters.
.TP
.B R
.I Replay position,
allows you to skip around in a log file when replaying an old game.
This key must be followed by either
.B f, p, c, n,
or
.B l.
These indicate you wish to see the
.I first, previous, current, next,
or
.B last
levels of the game.
The first time you enter the
.B R
command, there will be a pause of several seconds while the whole log
file is digested.
After this initialization, there should be no delay
when skipping around in the log file.
After you have skipped once, the
program won't terminate at the end of the file until you enter the
.B Q
.I (quit)
ommand.
This way you can replay the last level over (and over...).
.IR
.PP
When the game ends, either by your death, when you quit, or when
.B rogomatic
dies horribly of some bug, you will not get a list of the top-ten scorers.
The scoring is based entirely upon useless criteria anyway.
.B rogomatic
does keep a list of its games.
To see the best
.B rogomatic
games, use "rogomatic -s" which dumps the current scores in reverse order.
.PP
For more detailed directions, as the expression goes:
.B RTFS
(\fIhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RTFS\fP) :-).
See:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.I https://www.github.com/lcn2/rogomatic
.in -0.5i
.SH GENES
The
.B G
command lists the current settings for each
.BR rogomatic 's
``DNA'' settings.
These numbers (from 0 to 99) specify some of
.BR rogomatic 's
behaviors.
A gene pool file is kept in the score directory that
records the current population of explorers.
A variant of Holland's
``Genetic Algorithm'' is used to manipulate this gene pool.
The result
is that
.B rogomatic
learns from his past games how to play better.
The following genes are
currently used:
.TP
.B Sr
How many times to search each square for traps (0 to 4, depending on
amount of food and how far below level 7 he is).
.TP
.B Dr
How many times to search each square for secret doors (0 to 19, more for
dead end passages not in mazes).
.TP
.B Re
How much to rest up when injured (until 40% to 80% healed, based on
experience level).
.TP
.B Ar
When to shoot arrows at enemies, the higher the number, the more likely
.B rogomatic
is to shoot arrows at monsters (both smaller monsters, and more arrows).
.TP
.B Ex
How soon to experiment with unknown potions and scrolls (between levels
1 and 10).
.TP
.B Rn
How likely he is to run from an opponent (the higher the number, the sooner
he will run).
.TP
.B Wk
How likely he is to wake a sleeping opponent (the higher the number, the
bigger the monster he will attack, even though it is sleeping).
.TP
.B Fd
How likely he is to hoard extra food.
This affects how many rings he
wears, and how much he searches for traps.
.PP
.SH FILES
There are two executable files:
.B rogomatic
and
.BR player .
The
.B rogomatic
program is a small program which forks and execs the
.B rogue
game connected to the
.B player
program.
You must have access to all of these files.
.PP
These programs are searched for in the current directory.
If they are not found in the current directory, then, the
.B rogomatic
program
will look for then under the
.B @BINDIR@
directory.
.PP
By default,
.B rogomatic
creates
.B @RGMDIR@
known as the rogomatic directory.
.PP
The rogomatic directory may be changed by the command line option
.BR \-D \ path
command line option.
.PP
If the
.B \-d
command line option is used, various session related debugging files
are stored in a
.B UTC date and time
sub-directory of the form:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@ /YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS
is the year, month, day, hour, minute and second, in the UTC timezone,
of when player command started.
.PP
The rogomatic score file is kept in:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@/rgmscore version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
.PP
The rogomatic delta file is:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@/rgmdelta version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
If this file does not exist, it is created.
.PP
The gene pool is kept in:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@/GenePool version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
If this file does not exist, it is created.
.PP
A log of all mutations and crossovers is kept in:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@/GeneLog version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
If this file does not exist, it is created.
.PP
The long term memory of monster attributes is kept in:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@/ltm version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
If this file does not exist, it is created.
.PP
A log of internal errors and bugs is kept in:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.BI @RGMDIR@/error version
.in -0.5i
.sp
where
.I version
is the
.B rogue
version number, such as
.IR 5.4.5 .
If this file does not exist, it is created.
.SH OTHER PROGRAMS
.PP
Several programs are used to summarize and display
.BR rogomatic 's
performance.
The are installed under the
.B @BINDIR@
directory.
.PP
The
.I rgmgene
command summarizes the current population in the gene pool.
The
.I rgmscatter
command prints a scatter plot of all scores in the scorefile.
The
.I rgmhist
command prints a histogram of score (or levels if the
.B -l
option is given).
.SH SEE ALSO
rogue(6)
.SH SOURCE CODE
The source code for
.B rogomatic
is available is available at:
.PP
.in +0.5i
.I https://github.com/lcn2/rogomatic
.in -0.5i
.PP
in the form of a GitHub repo.
.PP
The above GitHub repo is maintained by:
.B Landon\ Curt\ Noll
( GitHub user
.BR @lcn2 :
.IR https://github.com/lcn2 \ )
and
GitHub user @jenoola ( \fIhttps://github.com/jenoola\fP ).
.PP
The port to ISO C 2017 with GNU extensions, the port to various platforms
such as NetBSD, Linux, and Cygwin, and many rogue bug fixes applied
by Landon Curt Noll user \fB@lcn2\fP, and the GitHub user \fB@jenoola\fP.
.SH BUGS
Occasionally
.B rogomatic
will dead-lock waiting for input from
.BR rogue .
When this happens, type an interrupt and enter the
.I t
command again.
This usually wakes it up enough to re-start the game.
In completely unusual cases, try interrupting and then entering the
.I S
command to save the game, and then re-start with "rogomatic -r".
Sometimes
you will have to use transparent mode to get it down to the next level
before turning it loose again.
.SH HISTORY
For a historic history of some changes, see the
.I ORIG_DOC/old.history.txt
file in the source directory.
